const e=JSON.parse('{"key":"v-0c49d9aa","path":"/blogs/Research/ArrayTrack.html","title":"ArrayTrack","lang":"zh-CN","frontmatter":{"title":"ArrayTrack","date":"2017-10-10T00:00:00.000Z","tag":["paper","CSI"],"category":["Research"],"description":"Abstract The presence of reflectors in the environment surrounding a transmitter and receiver create multiple paths that a transmitted signal can traverse. As a result, the receiver sees the superposition of multiple copies of the transmitted signal, each traversing a different path. Each signal copy will experience differences in attenuation, delay and phase shift while travelling from the source to the receiver. This can result in either constructive or destructive interference, amplifying or attenuating the signal power seen at the receiver. Strong destructive interference is frequently referred to as a deep fade and may result in temporary failure of communication due to a severe drop in the channel signal-to-noise ratio.","head":[["meta",{"property":"og:url","content":"https://vueblog.weigao.cc/blogs/Research/ArrayTrack.html"}],["meta",{"property":"og:site_name","content":"WW"}],["meta",{"property":"og:title","content":"ArrayTrack"}],["meta",{"property":"og:description","content":"Abstract The presence of reflectors in the environment surrounding a transmitter and receiver create multiple paths that a transmitted signal can traverse. As a result, the receiver sees the superposition of multiple copies of the transmitted signal, each traversing a different path. Each signal copy will experience differences in attenuation, delay and phase shift while travelling from the source to the receiver. This can result in either constructive or destructive interference, amplifying or attenuating the signal power seen at the receiver. Strong destructive interference is frequently referred to as a deep fade and may result in temporary failure of communication due to a severe drop in the channel signal-to-noise ratio."}],["meta",{"property":"og:type","content":"article"}],["meta",{"property":"og:locale","content":"zh-CN"}],["meta",{"property":"article:author","content":"Someone"}],["meta",{"property":"article:tag","content":"paper"}],["meta",{"property":"article:tag","content":"CSI"}],["meta",{"property":"article:published_time","content":"2017-10-10T00:00:00.000Z"}],["script",{"type":"application/ld+json"},"{\\"@context\\":\\"https://schema.org\\",\\"@type\\":\\"Article\\",\\"headline\\":\\"ArrayTrack\\",\\"image\\":[\\"\\"],\\"datePublished\\":\\"2017-10-10T00:00:00.000Z\\",\\"dateModified\\":null,\\"author\\":[{\\"@type\\":\\"Person\\",\\"name\\":\\"Someone\\",\\"url\\":\\"https://www.weigao.cc\\"}]}"]]},"headers":[{"level":2,"title":"Abstract","slug":"abstract","link":"#abstract","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Signal fade","slug":"signal-fade","link":"#signal-fade","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Two abservations","slug":"two-abservations","link":"#two-abservations","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Challenge","slug":"challenge","link":"#challenge","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Key observation","slug":"key-observation","link":"#key-observation","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"AoA","slug":"aoa","link":"#aoa","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Design","slug":"design","link":"#design","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Downconversion","slug":"downconversion","link":"#downconversion","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Useful word","slug":"useful-word","link":"#useful-word","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Relevant document","slug":"relevant-document","link":"#relevant-document","children":[]}],"git":{},"readingTime":{"minutes":1.73,"words":519},"filePathRelative":"blogs/Research/ArrayTrack.md","localizedDate":"2017年10月10日","excerpt":"<h2> Abstract</h2>\\n<p>The presence of reflectors in the environment surrounding a transmitter and receiver create multiple paths that a transmitted signal can traverse.</p>\\n<p>As a result, the receiver sees the <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superposition_principle\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">superposition</a> of multiple copies of the transmitted signal, each traversing a different path. Each signal copy will experience differences in <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attenuation\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">attenuation</a>, <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propagation_delay\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">delay</a> and <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phase_(waves)\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">phase shift</a> while travelling from the source to the receiver. This can result in either constructive or destructive interference, amplifying or attenuating the signal power seen at the receiver. Strong destructive interference is frequently referred to as a <strong>deep fade</strong> and may result in temporary failure of communication due to a severe drop in the channel <a href=\\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal-to-noise_ratio\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noopener noreferrer\\">signal-to-noise ratio</a>.</p>","autoDesc":true}');export{e as data};
